a)¶

The two most negatively correlated variables are regular-season wins in the year and runs allowed by the team in the year.

b)¶

The number of runs scored and the slugging percentage of the team for are the two most highly correlated variables.

c)¶

The number of games played in a year and the year of the record are the least correlated variables.

d)¶

There are 1s in the diagonal since the algorithm is checking a variable's correlation with itself.

b)¶

In [6]:

                     rotation=45,
                     horizontalalignment='right')
hmap
Out[6]:
<AxesSubplot:>

Most variables have a positive correlation which leads me to assume most variables are stats that are good for winning the game. Going with that I see that all most three variables (Year, Runs allowed, and Games played) that are correlated with wins are either not correlated or negatively correlated telling me that those are the only three variables not good for winning.

x = data.RA
x = sm.add_constant(x)
model = sm.OLS(y,x)
res = model.fit()
p = res.params
print(p)
print(res.summary())
